"Shen C., Wang W.-C., Gong W., Hao Z.","A Pacific Decadal Oscillation record since 1470 AD reconstructed from proxy data of summer rainfall over eastern China",2006,"Geophysical Research Letters","33","3", L03702,"","",,,10.1029/2005GL024804,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33645826273&partnerID=40&md5=9c57c6ead4c4b41bd3aae96d32834f67","Atmospheric Sciences Research Center, State University of New York, Albany, NY 12203, United States","Shen, C., Atmospheric Sciences Research Center, State University of New York, Albany, NY 12203, United States; Wang, W.-C., Atmospheric Sciences Research Center, State University of New York, Albany, NY 12203, United States; Gong, W., Atmospheric Sciences Research Center, State University of New York, Albany, NY 12203, United States; Hao, Z., Atmospheric Sciences Research Center, State University of New York, Albany, NY 12203, United States","Recent studies indicated that the spatial pattern and temporal variability of summer rainfall over eastern China are well correlated with the Pacific Decadal Oscillation (PDO). Here we used a data set of the drought/flood index (a proxy of summer rainfall) since 1470 AD to reconstruct the annual PDO index. The reconstruction indicates that the PDO is a robust feature of North Pacific climate variability throughout the study period, however, the major modes of oscillation providing the basic PDO regime timescale have not been persistent over the last 530 years. The quasi-centennial (75-115-yr) and pentadecadal (50-70-yr) oscillations dominated the periods before and after 1850, respectively. Our analysis suggest that solar forcing fluctuation on quasi-centennial time scale (Gleissberg cycle) could be the pace maker of the PDO before 1850, and the PDO behavior after 1850 could be due, in part, to the global warming. Copyright 2006 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric movements; Climate change; Correlation methods; Data structures; Rain; Regression analysis; Spectrum analysis; Climate variability; Pacific Decadal Oscillation; Peoples Republic of China; Quasi-centennial time scale; Climatology; climate variation; drought; flood; global warming; Pacific Decadal Oscillation; paleoclimate; rainfall; Asia; China; Eurasia; Far East",,,,,,"Biondi, F., Gershunov, A., Cayan, D.R., North Pacific decadal climate variability since 1661 (2001) J. Clim. Lett., 14, pp. 5-10; Birks, H.J.B., Quantitative paleoenvironmental reconstruction (1995) Statistical Modelling of Quaternary Science Data, pp. 161-254. , edited by D. Maddy and J. S. Brew, Quat. Res. Assoc., Cambridge, U. K; (1981) Yearly Charts of Dryness/Wetness in China for the Last 500-Year Period, , Chinese National Meteorological Administration Chin Cartogr. Publ. House, Beijing; D'Arrigo, R., Villalba, R., Wiles, G., Tree-ring estimates of Pacific decadal climate variability (2001) Clim. Dyn., 18, pp. 219-224; Ding, Y., (1991) Monsoons Over China, p. 419. , Springer, New York; Folland, C.K., Parker, D.E., Colman, A.W., Washington, R., Large scale modes of ocean surface temperature since the late nineteenth century (1999) Beyond El Nino: Decadal and Interdecadal Climate Variability, pp. 73-102. , edited by Navarra A., Springer, New York; Friis-Christensen, E., Lassen, K., Length of the solar cycle: An indicator of solar activity closely associated with climate (1991) Science, 254, pp. 698-700; Gedalof, Z., Smith, D.J., Interdecadal climate variability and regime-scale shifts in Pacific North America (2001) Geophys. Res. Lett., 28, pp. 1515-1518; Gedalof, Z., Mantua, N.J., Peterson, D.L., A multi-century perspective of variability in the Pacific Decadal Oscillation: New insights from tree rings and coral (2002) Geophys. Res. Lett., 29 (24), p. 2204. , doi:10.1029/2002GL015824; Ghil, M., Advanced spectral methods for climatic time series (2002) Rev. Geophys., 40 (1), p. 1003. , doi:10.1029/2000RG000092; Gong, D., He, X., Interdacadal change in western Pacific subtropical high and climati